LUMPY SKIN DISEASE, BOVINE - UGANDA: EAST, SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Sun 22 Aug 2010
Source: Sunday Monitor [edited]
<http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/-/688334/993700/-/x4gx3h/-/>


Farmers in eastern Uganda have appealed for the government's
intervention following an outbreak of a cattle disease. The disease
has affected Kumi, Ngora and Soroti districts, Kumi Veterinary
doctor, Simon Peter Arionga said.

The disease, which the doctor attributes to Ciprox virus, leaves the
animals with a lumpy skin. He said the disease causes fever and
nodules on the skin; lumps appear on the bodies of affected animals
which later turn into deep wounds. If not treated fast, the ailment
can result in deaths of the animals.

Dr Arionga said that the disease is caused by Capripox virus, which
was 1st discovered in Zambia in 1929.

He said the disease causes loss of appetite, discharge of saliva and
a grey discharge from the eyes. Dr Arionga identified the worst hit
sub-counties as Kapir, Kobuin in Ngora, Nyero in Kumi and Gweri in
Soroti. "There is need to isolate the sick animals from those that
have not yet contracted the disease," he said.

He added that the disease causes economic problems among cattle
keepers because milk production decreases, with weight loss, retarded
growth and damage to the hides.

Dr Arionga, who said there is need for massive vaccination of cattle,
said the disease can also be transmitted by insects. Mr Julius Ebaju,
a cattle keeper at Kapir communal grazing field in Kapir Sub-county,
said 20 head of cattle have already died because of the illness.

"We are trying to treat the animals using local herbs, but we have
failed to contain the disease," Mr Ebaju said. He said he gets dead
carcasses at their grazing fields daily.

[Byline: John Amodoi]

