Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Though lumpy skin disease (LSD) is regarded to be endemic in Uganda,
the most recent quantitative data, available from OIE's WAHID system,
dates back to 2005 (7 outbreaks in 5 provinces). Since then, Uganda
reported that the disease was suspected but not confirmed. Official
information on the current reported outbreak would be appropriate,
preferably lab confirmed.

OIE's LSD world distribution map for 2009 is available at
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=disease_status_map&disease_type=Terrestrial&disease_id=7&empty=999999&disease_serotype=0&sta_method=semesterly&selected_start_year=2009&selected_report_period=1&selected_start_month=1&page=disease_status_map&date_submit=OK>.

Lumpy skin disease (LSD, knopvelsiekte) is a pox disease of cattle
characterised by fever; nodules on the skin, mucous membranes and
internal organs; emaciation; enlarged lymph nodes; oedema of the
skin, and sometimes death. The disease is of economic importance
because it causes reduced production, particularly in dairy herds. It
also causes damage to the hide. LSD is caused by strains of
capripoxvirus that are antigenically indistinguishable from strains
causing sheep pox and goat pox. However, LSD has a different
geographical distribution to sheep and goat pox, suggesting that
cattle strains of capripoxvirus do not infect and transmit between
sheep and goats.

Transmission of LSD virus is thought to be predominantly by insects,
natural contact transmission in the absence of insect vectors being
inefficient. Until 1988, LSD was confined to sub-Saharan Africa, but
in 1988 spread into Egypt, where it has become endemic. So far, LSD
has been laboratory-confirmed only in 2 countries outside Africa,
Israel and Reunion.

The 1st outbreak in Israel occurred in 1989, most probably
originating from Egypt. It was eradicated by stamping out and ring
vaccinations. The disease recurred in Israel in 2006 (one outbreak)
and 2007 (7 outbreaks), all resolved by "modified stamping out" and
ring vaccination. In Reunion, LSD was diagnosed in 1993; Reunion, one
of the overseas territories of France, politically a part of the
Eurozone, is an island in the Indian ocean, 200 km from Mauritius. An
outbreak was reported in Bahrain, another ex-African country, in 1993
but was not confirmed by virus isolation. There was also an outbreak
in 2000 in cattle imported into Mauritius; the diagnosis was
confirmed by electron microscopy.

Further information concerning LSD diagnosis and vaccines is
available at
<http://oie.int/eng/normes/mmanual/2008/pdf/2.04.14_LSD.pdf>. In case
mass vaccination is applied during the disease season, special
attention should be paid to avoid spread of the virus between
vaccinated farms by frequent change of the syringe needles.

Pictures of clinical cases and gross pathology of LSD are available
at <http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/DiseaseInfo/ImageDB/imagesLSD.htm>. - Mod.AS]
